  "text": "Pulse height and timing information were extracted from the sampled data using the Optimal Filtering (OF) technique [CITATION_1] . This is the standard procedure in use by the ATLAS Liquid Argon Calorimeter group. It uses a simple but fast algebraic expression to calculate the peak amplitude and peak time from the pedestal-subtracted, time-ordered samples. The calculation requires a set of Optimal Filtering Coefficients (OFCs); derivation of these in turn requires a precise representation of the pulse shape and knowledge of the noise autocorrelation matrix, both of which can be obtained from the beam test data.",
